Using Custom Markers

Code

<!DOCTYPE html>

<html lang="en">

<head>

<meta charset="utf-8" />

<title>Using Custom Markers</title>

<style>

/* As always, place your CSS in an external file instead of embedding it
(it's embedded here to simplify the demo). */

ul {

/* turn off the default markers */

list-style: none;

/* set indentation of list items */

margin-left: 0;

padding-left: 15px;

}

li {

/* show image 2 pixels from top of item */

background: url(arrow-right.gif) no-repeat 0 2px;

/* bump the text over to make room for the arrow */

padding-left: 25px;

}

</style>

</head>

<body>

<h1>PageWhacker, version 12.0: Features</h1>

<ul>

<li>One click page layout</li>

<li>Spell checker for 327 major languages</li>

<li>Image retouching plug-in</li>

<li>Unlimited Undo's and Redo's</li>

<li>Automatic book writing</li>

</ul>

</body>

</html>

Output

[[file:media/image94.png]]

Controlling Where Markers Hang

Code

<!DOCTYPE html>

<html lang="en">

<head>

<meta charset="utf-8" />

<title>Controlling where Markers Hang</title>

<style>

/* As always, place your CSS in an external file instead of embedding it
(it's embedded here to simplify the demo). */

li {

list-style-position: inside;

}

</style>

</head>

<body>

<h1>PageWhacker, version 12.0: Features</h1>

<ul>

<li>One-click page layout. (This is particularly useful when you're
under a heavy deadline. You just select

whether you want the end product to be a book or a Web site, and poof,
it's done!)</li>

<li>Spell checker for 327 major languages</li>

<li>Image retouching plug-in</li>

<li>Unlimited Undo's and Redo's</li>

<li>Automatic book writing</li>

</ul>

</body>

</html>

